```c
void reverse(int arr[], int start, int end) {
    while (start < end) {
        int temp = arr[start];
        arr[start] = arr[end];
        arr[end] = temp;
        start++;
        end--;
    }
}

void rotateLeft(int arr[], int n, int d) {
    d = d % n; // handle d > n
    reverse(arr, 0, d - 1);    // reverse first d elements
    reverse(arr, d, n - 1);    // reverse remaining
    reverse(arr, 0, n - 1);    // reverse entire array
}
```
Reversal algorithm: reverse first d, reverse rest, reverse all. Time: O(n), Space: O(1). Handle d > n with modulo.

```c
void swap(int *a, int *b) {
    int temp = *a;
    *a = *b;
    *b = temp;
}
// Usage: swap(&x, &y);
```
Without pointers, C passes arguments by value — the function receives copies, so changes don't affect the original. With pointers, we pass the addresses, so we can modify the actual variables in the caller's scope. This is why swap(int a, int b) without pointers would only swap the local copies.

