```c
int gcd(int a, int b) {
    if (b == 0) return a;
    return gcd(b, a % b);
}
```
Euclid's algorithm: GCD(a, b) = GCD(b, a mod b). Base case: when b is 0, GCD is a. Example: GCD(48, 18) → GCD(18, 12) → GCD(12, 6) → GCD(6, 0) → 6. Time: O(log(min(a,b))). This is one of the oldest known algorithms.

Use the Sieve of Eratosthenes: assume all numbers are prime, then repeatedly mark multiples of each prime starting from its square as composite. Count what remains:
```
int countPrimes(int n) {
  if (n < 2) return 0;
  boolean[] composite = new boolean[n + 1];
  int count = 0;
  for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
    if (!composite[i]) {
      count++;
      for (long j = (long) i * i; j <= n; j += i) composite[(int) j] = true;
    }
  }
  return count;
}
```
Time O(n log log n), space O(n). A naive trial-division check per number is O(n*sqrt(n)) and acceptable for small n but the sieve is the standard answer.

Two strings are rotations of each other iff they are the same length and one is a substring of the other concatenated with itself. Any rotation of s appears inside s+s:
```
boolean isRotation(String a, String b) {
  return a.length() == b.length() && (a + a).contains(b);
}
```
Example: a+a = "abcdeabcde" contains "cdeab", so true. This is O(n) with an efficient substring search (e.g., KMP); the naive contains is O(n^2) worst case but fine for interview scale.
